Clustering Wholesale Customers

Dataset:

Shekhar, R. (2017). Wholesale customers Data Set, Version 1. Retrieved Nov 27, 2024 from https://www.kaggle.com/datasets/binovi/wholesale-customers-data-set/data.

Project and Goal:

This project will be analyzing a dataset containing annual spending by clients of a wholesale distributor. Various unsupervised learning techniques such as KMeans clustering and Hierarchical clustering will be used to uncover patterns, groupings, and insights.

The goal of this project will be to group customers into distinct clusters based on their spending habits across product categories. This will help identify customer profiles and tailor strategies for each group.

This dataset is a single table that contains 440 rows and 8 columns. Each row represents a customer and each column contains an attribute. Two of the categories are categorical while the other six are continuous. An explanation of each of the columns (along with their data type) can be seen below:

  • Channel: Horeca (Hotel/Restaurant/Cafe) ("1") or Retail ("2") - (Nominal)
  • Region: Lisnon ("1"), Oporto ("2") or Other ("3") - (Nominal)
  • Fresh: Annual spending on fresh products - (Continuous)
  • Milk: Annual spending on milk products - (Continuous)
  • Grocery: Annual spending on grocery products - (Continuous)
  • Frozen: Annual spending on frozen products - (Continuous)
  • Detergents_Paper: Annual spending on detergents and paper products - (Continuous)
  • Delicassen: Annual spending on delicassen (fine, exotic, or foreign prepared foods) products - (Continuous)

In[285]:
def outliers(data, column):
    q1 = data[column].quantile(0.25)
    q3 = data[column].quantile(0.75)
    IQR = q3 - q1
    lower_bound = q1 - 1.5 * IQR
    upper_bound = q3 + 1.5 * IQR

    def clip_value(x):
        if x < lower_bound:
            return lower_bound
        elif x > upper_bound:
            return upper_bound
        else:
            return x

    data[column] = data[column].apply(clip_value)

outliers(data2, 'Fresh')
outliers(data2, 'Milk')
outliers(data2, 'Grocery')
outliers(data2, 'Frozen')
outliers(data2, 'Detergents_Paper')
outliers(data2, 'Delicassen')

This visual provides us a lot of information about each of the clusters:

Cluster 0:

  • "Fresh" is the dominant category with significantly higher spending than the rest of the categories
  • The rest of the categories have relatively low spending

Cluster 1:

  • "Grocery" and "Milk" have high spending among this cluster
  • "Frozen" and "Delicassen" spending is notably lower

Cluster 2:

  • This cluster has the same spending distribution as cluster 0
  • The difference comes from the spending level where among all categories, spending is double what it is in cluster 0

Cluster 3:

  • "Fresh", "Grocery", and "Milk" are the dominating categories but not significantly
  • Spending is more balanced across categories compated to the other clusters

If we were to implement this knowledge into a business plan/strategy, I would recommend implementing targeted marketing for each cluster. This would include promoting fresh produce bundles for customers in cluster 0 and 2. I would suggest larger bundles for those in cluster 2 and smaller bundles for those in cluster 0 in order to align the deal with their spending habits. I would also offer bulk discounts in for grocery and milk products for those in cluster 1. For customers in cluster 3, I would suggest diversified offers that focus on combo packages that span across multiple categories.

Result and Analysis

In[302]:
print("Inertia without PCA:", kmeans.inertia_)
print("Inertia with PCA:", kmeans_pca.inertia_)

Inertia without PCA: 2274027907.32977
Inertia with PCA: 5657884299.6032

The inertia of KMeans model without PCA is about 2.24E10. The inertia of the KMeans model with PCA is about 5.65E9. A lower inertia indicates better compactness of clusters therefore the clustering model with PCA is the better model.

Let's confirm this with a different evaluation metric.

We will use silhouette score which measures cluster compactness.

In[303]:
sil_original = silhouette_score(data2, y_kmeans)
sil_pca = silhouette_score(data3, pca_kmeans)

print("Silhouette Score without PCA:", sil_original)
print("Silhouette Score with PCA:", sil_pca)

Silhouette Score without PCA: 0.35703470092173456
Silhouette Score with PCA: 0.45798488452610064

We can see the silhouette score of the model with PCA is higher than that of the model without PCA. This means that clusters produced by the clustering model with PCA resulted in clusters that are more compact therefore the clustering works better after reducing correlated features.

Let's scale up our 'PCA_Components' category:

In[304]:
original_variances = data2[['Fresh', 'Frozen', 'Delicassen']].var()
mean_original_variance = original_variances.mean()

pca_variance = data3['PCA_Component'].var()

scaling_factor = (mean_original_variance / pca_variance) ** 0.5

data3['PCA_Component'] *= scaling_factor

print("Original Features Variance (mean):", mean_original_variance)
print("Scaled PCA Component Variance:", data3['PCA_Component'].var())

Original Features Variance (mean): 37082844.3270214
Scaled PCA Component Variance: 37082844.32702137

Analysis:

Observations of the final clusters:

  • Cluster 0 retains a strong focus on Fresh products
  • Cluster 1 shows extreme spending on Fresh products even more than before PCA
  • Cluster 2 is similar to cluster 1 but at a lower magnitude (lower spending)
  • Cluster 3 has more balanced spending among the different categories in comparison to the other clusters
  • Cluster 3 exhibits a large variance for the PCA component which suggests that this dimension capures significant variance

Overall analysis of the final clusters:

  • "Fresh" is the dominant product category across all clusters
    • This is emphasized after PCA was performed
  • "Frozen" and "Delicassen" show significantly lower spending levels compared to Fresh

Based off the clusters and the analysis, I would suggest for the business to focus on marketing fresh produce for all customers, bulk discounts for fresh produce for those in cluster 0, large bulk discounts for those in cluster 1 and 2, and diversified offers for those in cluster 3.

Other Clustering Methods:

What if we want more or less than 4 clusters?

Hierarchical Clustering:

In[307]:
plt.figure(figsize = (18,8))
sc.dendrogram(sc.linkage(data, method='ward'))
plt.show()

While 4 clusters seems to be the point at which the rate of decrease of inertia slows down, We might possibly want to create a lower or higher number of clusters.

The dendrogram above groups data points by merging similar clusters until all data points are included in a single cluster at the top of the hierarchy. The height represents the distance (dissimilarity) between the clusters while branches represent the merging of data points.

Discussion and Conclusion:

Discussion:

The clustering analysis on the wholesale customer dataset revealed important insights both before and after applying PCA. These results allowed us to identify key spending patterns among clusters and allows us to implement this knowledge into a business plan/strategy. One of the big insights this data provided is the importance of marketing different deals to different customers. While each customer has different needs, this technique increases the likelihood that their needs are met so that they are more likely to shop at that wholesale store.

Key Takeaway

This project showed how PCA adds value in distinguishing complex patterns as the scaled PCA components introduced variability that helped capture patterns not visible in the raw data. However, 'Fresh' remained dominance after PCA which suggested that it is a primary driver of variability in this dataset.

Challenges:

After performing PCA, the components were initially miniscule to the original features. An additional step of scaling the PCA_Components had to be taken and even then, interpreting it in a real-world context can be challenging since they are abstract representations instead of tangible product categories.

Suggestions for Improvement:

Feature Engineering:

We can potentially engineer new features such as ratios between categories which can help PCA uncover more subtle patterns and reduce the dominance of a single category (in our case - 'Fresh').

Alternative Dimensionality Reduction Techniques:

We can explote t-SNE for dimensionality reduction. This technique can possibly capture patterns that PCA might have missed if the relationships are non-linear between features.

Clustering Enhancements:

We can use different clustering methods such as DBSCAN to identify clusters of different shapes that KMeans might miss.

Conclusion:

This analysis highlights how PCA and KMeans clustering can be powerful tools for uncovering patterns. The pre-PCA clustering provides clear and interpretable insights, while post-PCA clustering offers a higher-level understanding of broader behavioral trends. However, there are associated challenges with PCA that include interpretability, therefore further refinements to the data preprocessing and clustering methodology are needed.

Ultimately, looking at both the pre- and post-PCA approaches allows for detailed insights from the original categories and broader trends from PCA components. This can provide a comprehensive understanding of customer behavior. Future work can focus on exploring advanced dimensionality reduction techniques to better capture the complexity of wholesale customer spending patterns or feature engineering to reduce the dominance of a single category.
